under Howard Pyle at Drexel University 1894. Illustrated 60+ books including Louisa May Alcott's Little Women, Robert Louis Stevenson's A Child's Garden of Verses, and Longfellow's Evangeline. Created all Good Housekeeping covers Dec 1917 to 1933. \"One of the greatest pure illustrators\" of the early 20th century. Lived with \"The Red Rose Girls\" (Elizabeth Shippen Green, Violet Oakley) — a celebrated artistic household in Villanova PA. Never married; no children. Descendant of Thomas Hooker through: Jesse Hart → Harriet Hart Willcox → Katherine Willcox Smith → Jessie Willcox Smith. Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessie_Willcox_Smith","gender":"female","marriages":[],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["arts"],"notable_blurb":"Foremost American children's-book illustrator of her era","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jessie_Willcox_Smith","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"TD0241","display_label":"Followed at PAFA next generation; Mary Smith Prize 1908 and 1912","link_text":"Elizabeth Sparhawk-Jones"},{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD5941","display_label":"a fellow woman who broke into commercial art"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Jessie Willcox Smith","first_name":"Jessie","middle_name":"Willcox","maiden_name":"Smith","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST141","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1885-1888","institution_blurb":"Studied at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts under Thomas Eakins."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Sixteen years of Good Housekeeping covers","body":"She illustrated every monthly cover of Good Housekeeping from December 1917 through April 1933 — nearly two hundred paintings of children, mothers, and seasonal moments. Those covers shaped a generation's image of American childhood."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Defined the look of Heidi and Mother Goose","body":"Her illustrations for The Water-Babies (1916), Little Women (1915), Heidi (1922), and A Child's Garden of Verses (1905) became the definitive editions of those books for two generations of American readers. She turned down film and theater commissions to keep illustration as her sole career."},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"Studied under Eakins and Howard Pyle","body":"She trained at the Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts under Thomas Eakins and at Drexel under Howard Pyle, the foremost American illustrator of his generation. Pyle reportedly called her one of his most gifted students."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Three women artists ran a household together","body":"She lived with fellow illustrators Violet Oakley and Elizabeth Shippen Green at 'Cogslea,' a converted inn outside Philadelphia. The three built independent careers, traveled together, and supported each other's work for nearly thirty years."}],"education":[{"institution_id":"INST141","type":"art_academy","dates":"1885-1888","notes":"Studied under Thomas Eakins; later trained with Howard Pyle at Drexel."}],"career":[{"role":"Illustrator","start_year":1888,"end_year":1935,"notes":"Good Housekeeping cover artist for sixteen years; illustrated Heidi, Mother Goose, and other classics."}],"slug":"jessie-smith-1863"},"X02013":{"id":"X02013","is_placeholder":false,"gender":"male","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1798,"month":6,"day":14},"death":{"year":1869,"month":6,"day":2},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM009"},"parents":{},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"HD0726","children_ids":["HD2965","HD0731"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"FindAGrave"}],"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["law","politics"],"notable_blurb":"The marshal who held the Amistad captives","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amistad_(schooner)","primary_url_label":"Amistad case — Wikipedia"},"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"law","header":"The marshal who held the Amistad captives","body":"Appointed United States Marshal for Connecticut by Andrew Jackson in 1831, Willcox took custody of the kidnapped Africans of the schooner Amistad when they were brought to New Haven in 1839. He held them through the long case that climbed to the Supreme Court.","number":1},{"category":"law","header":"He later carried out the captives' release","body":"When the courts ruled for the Africans, it fell to Willcox to free them from federal custody. President Polk afterward named him collector of customs for the port of New Haven.","number":2}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"legal_adversary_ally","related_id":"HD0867","display_label":"Both central figures in the Amistad case — Willcox as federal marshal holding the captives, Leavitt as the abolitionist organizing their legal defense.","link_text":"Rev. Joshua Leavitt"},{"type":"amistad_connection","related_id":"H00697","display_label":"Cowles housed a Mende girl in his Farmington home after the Supreme Court freed the captives; Willcox had administered their federal custody throughout the trial.","link_text":"Horace Cowles"},{"type":"amistad_connection","related_id":"H00698","display_label":"Held the Mende during trial — Cowles housed one after release","link_text":"Major Timothy Cowles","description":"Norris Willcox held the Mende captives in federal custody during their trial. After the Supreme Court freed them in March 1841, the Mende were brought to Farmington, where Major Timothy Cowles was among the families who sheltered one of the freed Mende girls."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Norris Willcox","first_name":"N